    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix unpacking of system information schedule request for unsupported RAT types\n\n### Summary\nThe `unpack_system_information_schedule_request` function in the nFAPI library incorrectly handled messages with unsupported RAT types. When processing a message with an unsupported RAT type (e.g., UTRAN or GERAN), the function would attempt to validate TLV tags that were never unpacked, leading to incorrect validation failures and potential crashes.\n\nThis issue occurred because the function always validated both LTE and NB-IOT TLV tags regardless of the actual `rat_type` in the message. For unsupported RAT types, neither TLV was unpacked, so their tag fields contained uninitialized data.\n\n### Changes\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/nfapi/src/nfapi_p4.c`: Modified `unpack_system_information_schedule_request` to:\n  - Only unpack TLVs relevant to the message's `rat_type`\n  - Only validate TLV tags that were actually unpacked\n  - Handle unsupported RAT types gracefully\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce this issue:\n1. Send a system information schedule request message with `rat_type` set to `NFAPI_RAT_TYPE_UTRAN` (value 1)\n2. Ensure the message contains only the common PNF cell broadcast state TLV\n3. Observe that the function fails validation even though the message structure is correct\n4. In some cases, this may cause a segfault due to accessing uninitialized memory in the TLV structures\n\nThe fix ensures that only the appropriate TLVs are processed for each RAT type, matching the behavior of the corresponding packing function.\n"
}